[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(10) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Think an evil thought.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 38:10-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the motives of Gog in his attack upon Israel are fully exposed. It is to be remembered that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 38:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 38:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the leading of this foe against the Church is represented as God’s own act; here it is explained that God did this by allowing him to follow out the devices of his own heart.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Ezekiel 38:10-13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ezekiel 38:10-13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "It shall come to pass at the same time — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The time when my people are gathered together, settled in peace in their own land, and think themselves secure; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "shall things come into thy mind ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Mischievous things; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and thou shalt think an evil thought — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Shalt entertain a malicious design for the destruction of my people. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And thou shalt say — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Wilt resolve in thyself; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I will go up — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I will invade with all my forces; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the land of unwalled villages — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A people weak, and destitute of any considerable defences. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "To them that are at rest — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who would willingly be quiet, and suspect as little evil from others as they intend against others, and who trust in the protection of their God, who hath promised they shall dwell safely. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Dwelling without walls, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — That is, having no sufficient fortifications to defend them against the force of an enemy. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "To take a spoil,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " &c. — With the thoughts of taking a large spoil without any difficulty. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "To turn thy hand upon the desolate places — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To go against, or fall upon, a country which had lain a long time desolate, but which has been peopled again, and come into a flourishing condition. Judea is very plainly marked out by this land, which Gog is here represented as designing to attack, because it lay open to be invaded. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "That dwell in the midst of the land — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in the navel of the land, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that is, in Jerusalem, which stood nearly in the middle of Judea, and was situate upon a rising ground, which the Hebrew metaphorically expresses by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the navel. Sheba and Dedan, and the merchants of Tarshish — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "These were people that traded much, the two former dwelling in the east, and the merchants of Tarshish often sailing from the Spanish coasts into the eastern parts, as having commerce with Tyre, which bordered upon Judea. “These merchants, as soon as they heard of this intended invasion, came into Gog’s camp as to a market, to buy both persons and goods which should come into the conqueror’s power.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "With all the young lions thereof — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Their kings and princes, as the Targum understands it; or their chief merchants, who are described as so many princes, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) and are called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "lions ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "because of the injustice and oppression they too commonly practised in their commerce.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "38:1-13 These events will be in the latter days. It is supposed these enemies will come together to invade the land of Judea, and God will defeat them. God not only sees who are now the enemies of his church, but he foresees who will be so, and lets them know by his word that he is against them; though they join together, the wicked shall not be unpunished.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As Gog was drawn on to his attack upon Israel in order to his ultimate ruin, therefore his preparations were the first step in his visitation from the Almighty.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After many days - For \"many days.\" Many a long day shall the hand of God be upon thee, drawing thee on to thy ruin, and in the latter days shalt thou come.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The land - literally, a \"land\" once laid waste by the sword, but now delivered from it, whose inhabitants once scattered have been gathered together from out of many peoples.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Always - Rather, a long time. The mountains were at the time of Gog's advance again cultivated and populous.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And they shall dwell - Rather, and they dwell. It is a description of the actual condition at the time of Gog's invasion (compare Judges 18:7). Such was the condition of the restored Jews in their prosperous days, after which came invasion. Such shall be the condition of the Church previous to the final conflict between good and evil. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And they shall dwell - Rather, and they dwell. It is a description of the actual condition at the time of Gog's invasion (compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Judges 18:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). Such was the condition of the restored Jews in their prosperous days, after which came invasion. Such shall be the condition of the Church previous to the final conflict between good and evil. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "10. an evil thought—as to attacking God's people in their defenseless state.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
